<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-29T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-29T20:00:00-05:00" n="849" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d849">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) Eastern Publishing
                            Co./30: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-30T09:00:00+08:00">December 30, 1937—9
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 30—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1248. Reference my despatch No. 956 of September 11, 1937, and previous
                            communications regarding “<hi rend="italic">Voice of China</hi>”
                            published by Eastern Publishing Company, owned by Max Granich.
                            Settlement police report that Mr. and Mrs. Max Granich left Shanghai on
                            December 21, 1937, on the steamship <hi rend="italic">Ranpura</hi>
                            destined for Marseille, France.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>